learning_outcomes.description: Critically investigate the internet, new media and digital technologies.
Understand and use key concepts in the study of digital cultures.
Analyse digital cultures from historical, philosophical, aesthetic, sociological and political perspectives.
Think and write critically about the impact of digital media and technology on everyday life.

assessments.category: Notebook/ Logbook, Participation/ Student contribution, Reflection
assessments.task_description:
You will complete structured entries in a learning journal each week during the course (not in Weeks 2, 6 or 10). This assessment is designed to check your understanding of key concepts from the readings and tutorial activities, your ability to apply those concepts, and your participation in tutorials. Learning journal entries will be handwritten in class and collected by your tutor for assessment each week. This is a device-free assessment. Use of AI is not permitted for this assessment. Journal entries can only be completed in class. Each week's journal entry is worth 6 points. Your final mark will be calculated from your highest 5 results across 8 weeks (5 weeks x 6 points = 30 points).

Each weekly learning journal entry will comprise two parts:

1.    Questions on lectures and readings (4 points)

Questions will vary and may include: short answer responses, multiple choice items, or tasks based on visual material shown in class. 

2.    Evidence of class participation (2 points)

You will write one or two sentences. You should describe the type of contribution you made: e.g. asking a question, responding to discussion, offering feedback to peers, assisting a classmate with activities. You should also provide specific evidence of your contribution: eg, “I shared a TikTok about beauty filters to show how algorithms shape representation and gender”; “I was confused about the reading and asked a question about it in class.”


AI Policy

This assessment task is to be completed in-person. The use of generative Artificial Intelligence (AI) or Machine Translation (MT) tools will not be permitted. Any attempted use of AI or MT may constitute student misconduct under the Student Code of Conduct.
assessments.submission_guidelines: Your tutor will collect your journal entries, and they will be scanned and marked in Gradescope
assessments.deferral_or_extension: You cannot defer or apply for an extension for this assessment.
assessments.late_submission: Journal entries can only be completed in class. Late submission is not possible for this assessment.
assessments.additional_info: You cannot defer or apply for an extension for this assessment.

assessments.category: Creative Production/ Exhibition, Paper/ Report/ Annotation, Product/ Design
assessments.task_description:
For this assessment, you will create a 90-second reel-style video introducing a new keyword in digital cultures — not one we have studied in the course but a new keyword that comes from your own generation, culture, or online experience.

The aim is to explain the keyword clearly and creatively for an audience encountering it for the first time, and to show how it connects to the ideas and concepts discussed in the course. Your reels will be screened in the final tutorial of Module 1 (Week 6) as part of a shared “New Keywords in Digital Cultures” showcase. You will submit your completed Process File by at the end of Week 6, Thursday 2 April.


This assessment consists of two parts:

1: Keyword Reel

Choose one new digital culture keyword from your own generation, culture, or online experience—not one we have studied in class. Create a video of no more than 90 seconds in a style or format of your choice (e.g. commentary, parody, storytelling, screen-based walkthrough). Your reel should include:

  • what the keyword means
  • where it appears (platforms, communities, practices)
  • why it matters for digital culture (e.g. relates to issues of power, identity, platform dynamics, representation etc)

Your video must include your voice, image, or screen presence and be your own work.

2: Process File

You must also submit a short process file (700-800 words) that:

  • includes your planning ideas and notes
  • explains how you chose and developed the keyword
  • outlines how you made the video, why you chose your format or style
  • shows how course readings or concepts helped shape your explanation
  • includes a formatted bibliography and AI use declaration, as well as full AI use documentation, if needed


AI Policy

Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Translation (MT) are emerging tools that may support students in completing this assessment task. Students may appropriately use AI and/or MT in completing this assessment task. Students must clearly reference any use of AI or MT in each instance. A failure to reference generative AI or MT use may constitute student misconduct under the Student Code of Conduct.

assessments.category: Paper/ Report/ Annotation, Essay/ Critique, Portfolio
assessments.task_description:
In this assessment, you will investigate a current “hot topic” in digital culture by building a digital case file. Rather than writing a traditional research essay, you will collect, organise, and evaluate evidence from digital culture itself. This assessment consists of two parts:

1.    You will choose a contemporary issue (e.g. platform governance, AI and creativity, online activism or radicalization, data use, digital identity, content moderation) and compile a digital case file of relevant material (posts, images, videos, articles, platform features, policy documents, media coverage).Your case file should consist of a single document that includes 8–12 items of digital evidence, such as:

·      social media posts or threads

·      platform features or interfaces

·      online articles or policy statements

·      images, videos, or memes

Provide brief captions for each item explaining why it is relevant or interesting

2.    You will then write a case file report (1200 words) that evaluates this topic and material using ideas from lectures and readings in COMU1500. Your report should:

·      explain the chosen topic and why it matters

·      evaluate the collected evidence and uses that evidence to advance an argument or analysis

·      engage with course concepts, lectures, and readings in detail, including direct citations that are actively used to advance a position or argue a debate

·      reflect on issues such as power, representation, participation, surveillance, identity, or automation

Your report must include a formatted bibliography that includes course readings, an AI use declaration and, if required, full AI use documentation.


AI Policy

Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Translation (MT) are emerging tools that may support students in completing this assessment task. Students may appropriately use AI and/or MT in completing this assessment task. Students must clearly reference any use of AI or MT in each instance. A failure to reference generative AI or MT use may constitute student misconduct under the Student Code of Conduct.
